  "prompt": "Should universities be elitist?",
  "response": "Whether universities should be elitist is a complex issue with strong arguments on both sides.\n\nArguments for universities being more meritocratic (which can be seen as a form of elitism) often emphasize that these institutions should be centers of excellence, selecting the most talented and promising individuals to drive innovation and progress. By admitting the best students, regardless of their background, universities can foster a competitive environment that pushes everyone to achieve their full potential. Additionally, focusing on merit can lead to graduates who are highly skilled and capable, benefiting society as a whole. Some might argue that resources are limited, and concentrating them on the most promising students yields the greatest return for society.\n\nOn the other hand, arguments against elitism in universities highlight the importance of equal opportunity and social mobility. Education is seen as a fundamental right, and limiting access based on arbitrary criteria can perpetuate existing inequalities. A more diverse student body can bring a wider range of perspectives and experiences to the university, enriching the learning environment for everyone. Moreover, focusing solely on academic merit may overlook other valuable qualities, such as creativity, leadership, and resilience. Some believe that universities have a responsibility to address historical disadvantages and promote social justice by actively recruiting and supporting students from underrepresented backgrounds.\n\nUltimately, the ideal approach likely lies somewhere in the middle. Universities should strive for excellence while also ensuring that access is not limited to a privileged few. This could involve a holistic admissions process that considers a variety of factors beyond academic\u6210\u7ee9, as well as robust financial aid programs to support students from low-income backgrounds. Striking the right balance between merit and equity is essential for creating a university system that benefits both individuals and society as a whole.",
